ons will address the aspects and implications of this issue:</p><ol><li><p>In Section 2, an empirical theory of ideology will be sketched to guide discussions of harmful ideological bias over fields of inquiry.</p></li><li><p>In Section 3, evidence pointing to the presence of widespread political bias of a "left-wing" or "progressive" variety throughout Western higher education institutions, including academic philosophy, will be reviewed.</p></li><li><p>In Section 4, a speculative etiology of PC will be presented, and the content of several beliefs associated with PC will be formalized to understand the underlying worldview.</p></li><li><p>In Section 5, using formal constructs from applied science, the epistemic integrity of philosophy as a truth-seeking enterprise will be defended and how PC concerns of social justice may undermine the epistemic prowess of philosophy will be addressed.</p></li><li><p>In Section 6, three lines of argument relevant to the idea that philosophy requires socially progressive political values to be truth-seeking will be responded to.</p></li><li><p>In Section 7, tentative prescriptions on how to reverse existing harmful ideological effects due to political bias in academic philosophy will be discussed.</p></li></ol><p>Despite the seeming harmlessness of postmodernism, identified as one of the central progenitors of the ideology criticized here, it's important to note that it has generated virulent thought patterns which promote anti-scientific thinking, potentially leading to real-world harm. For instance, branding evidence-based medicine as "fascist" could influence the adoption of non-evidence-based medicine with possible loss of lives.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5