ct.</p></li><li><p><strong>Rationality of Silence on Certain Issues:</strong> A hypothetical scenario is presented where feminist activists might choose to not vocalize concerns about sexual violence perpetrated by Muslims. This could be because racism and xenophobia are considered higher on the "Hierarchy of Oppression" than sexism, making the criticism of a minority group a potentially greater moral transgression than addressing the issue of sexual violence.</p></li><li><p><strong>Anthropological Mental Egalitarianism (AME):</strong> This is defined as a core belief in the PC worldview, denying the existence of significant mental differences between socially oppressed groups and their oppressors. The differences discussed aren't about actual mental abilities, but about what they could be if the socially oppressive ideologies were removed.</p></li><li><p><strong>Importance of Maintaining AME:</strong> The author argues that questioning AME is highly taboo, potentially causing serious consequences, as illustrated with the example of Lawrence Summers, former president of Harvard University. His suggestion of natural differences in cognitive variability between men and women led to significant backlash and possible career implications.</p></li><li><p><strong>Inclusion of Mental Attributes:</strong> The author indicates that the "mental" aspects being considered include both general and specific cognitive, affective, and behavioral traits, covering a wide range of human characteristics.</p></li></ol><p>It's important to note that these are complex, debatable ideas and the summary is based on the author's interpretation of the topic, as presented in the text.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 