Aside from the pursuit of truth, which is an epistemic value, philosophy is influenced by a set of non-epistemic values. These non-epistemic values are extra-theoretical, social or ethical considerations, that guide and influence philosophical enquiry, such as fairness, inclusivity, representation, social justice, and political correctness (PC).</p><p>The addition of these non-epistemic values has stirred an ongoing debate in philosophical circles about the telos, or purpose, of philosophy. Does the inclusion of non-epistemic values, in particular PC, enhance or hinder the pursuit of philosophical truths?</p><p>On one side of the debate, proponents argue that the inclusion of non-epistemic values, especially PC, is necessary for a more equitable and socially conscious philosophy. They posit that these values encourage more diverse perspectives and problematics, enriching philosophical discourse and challenging entrenched biases.</p><p>On the other side, detractors contend that the inclusion of non-epistemic values, especially PC, potentially jeopardizes the epistemic integrity of philosophy. They worry that these values may unduly influence philosophical enquiry, leading to the suppression of controversial ideas, the elevation of social conformity over intellectual rigor, and the possible distortion of truth.</p><p>The challenge is to reconcile these seemingly opposing positions. A potential solution could be the application of principles from the field of engineering, which acknowledges the interplay between truth and non-epistemic values in its design processes. By adopting a similar approach, philosophy could navigate the tensions between truth-seeking and the need for non-epistemic values, while preserving its epistemic integrity.</p><p>The key is balance. Philosophy should strive to create an environment where both epistemic and non-epistemic values coexist without one dominating the other. This equilibrium, however, requires constant vigilance and self-reflection to ensure that the pursuit of truth remains the primary goal of philosophy, while non-epistemic values contribute to a more inclusive and socially conscious philosophical discourse.</p><p>5.4. The Threat of PC to Philosophy
As mentioned, one particular non-epistemic value that has gained prominence in recent years is political correctness (PC). PC advocates for the use of language and behavior to avoid offense and provide inclusivity, particularly to marginalized groups.</p><p>While PC aims to promote a more inclusive and respectful discourse, it can, in some cases, create a form of intellectual conformism that inhibits the free exchange of ideas, which is central to the philosophical endeavour. By placing constraints on what can be discussed or how it can be discussed, PC can potentially stifle intellectual rigor, challenge, and creativity.</p><p>Moreover, an excessive emphasis on PC may steer philosophy away from its truth-seeking goal. If philosophers begin to prioritize non-offensive or socially acceptable ideas over truthful ones, the epistemic integrity of philosophy is threatened. Philosophical enquiry could be reduced to ideological posturing or pandering to social trends, rather than a rigorous exploration of truth.</p><p>In conclusion, while non-epistemic values, including PC, can enrich philosophical discourse and promote a more inclusive environment, an unmoderated influence of these values can threaten the core epistemic goal of philosophy. Therefore, maintaining a balanced interplay between truth and non-epistemic values is essential for the continued growth and integrity of philosophy.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-