t may be more practical to use an ordinal approach, focusing on the order of importance rather than the exact value of each criterion.</p><p>There are limitations to this approach. For example, philosophers often work with informal theories that are not readily quantifiable, making the computation of specific values difficult. In this sense, epistemic appraisal may be a strictly ordinal endeavor.</p><p>The approach of using MCDA and MOO models also challenges some traditional doctrines in measurement theory. These models often treat ordinal variables as if they were interval or ratio-scalable, which can lead to extracting arithmetic means of arbitrary data and assuming that different levels of Likert-type scales are equally spaced magnitudes. In the absence of evidence that supports this assumption, one should be conservative and assume that the variables only meet the simpler and less demanding family of comparative structures.</p><p>Moving forward, the models and methods derived from fields like operations research can offer valuable insights into the process of epistemic appraisal in philosophy and other fields of inquiry. It is now time to explore some of the specific results these fields have produced that can be applied to the problem of epistemic appraisal.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" vie