developing efficient constructs as it tries to achieve more goals. This is indeed a common issue in MOO, known as the "curse of dimensionality", where the difficulty of finding optimal solutions grows exponentially with the number of objectives.</p><p>This approach can be critiqued from several perspectives, one being the representation of the process of knowledge production in a field of inquiry as a computational process, akin to a program implementable in a Turing machine. This assumes a deterministic, mechanistic model of knowledge production, which may not fully capture the complex, non-linear, and often intuitive processes involved in real-world decision-making. Moreover, it could be argued that human decision-makers might have more computational power than a classical Turing machine, thus making these constraints less relevant. However, even if we allow for this possibility, the problems of non-optimality and the curse of dimensionality still remain significant challenges for decision-making in fields of inquiry with multiple conflicting objectives.</p><p>Overall, your postulates highlight important insights into the complexities and difficulties of decision-making in fields with multiple conflicting goals. It serves as a reminder that decision-making is often an art of negotiation and compromise, and that finding a single optimal solution might not be possible or even desirable in many cases.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled=